In <1992Dec17.200225.27831@ulysses.att.com> smb@research.att.com (Steven Bellovin) writes:

>You're quite correct about RSA not being protected outside of the U.S.
>Within the U.S., a patent may be infringed by making, selling, or using
>the protected device.

A program is not a "device" under patent law, or you would be patenting an
algorithm, which we all know is improper.  It requires a program + computer
to infringe, and that means the user, (the one who puts them together)
might be the infringer.

